summary: >-
  Fixed a TypeScript regression in the gateway delivery report pipeline where summarize() crashed with
  TypeError when samples lacked a metrics field. Made metrics optional in the DeliverySample type, added a
  runtime guard in the aggregation loop, and added a targeted test covering samples with missing metrics. All
  5 tests pass, type checking passes, and the report command runs cleanly against real sample data.
diagnosis: >-
  The summarize() function in src/report.ts unconditionally accessed s.metrics.retries and
  s.metrics.latency_ms on every sample. However, real data (data/samples.json) contains a gw-04 sample with
  outcome 'rejected' and no metrics field, because the probe worker's measurement cycle had not yet completed.
  At runtime this produced: TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'retries'). The
  DeliverySample interface also declared metrics as required, masking the real-world possibility of absent
  metrics at the type level.
outputs:
  changed_files: >-
    src/types.ts (made metrics optional with updated JSDoc), src/report.ts (added if (s.metrics) guard in
    summarize loop), test/report.test.ts (added 'summarize handles samples with missing metrics gracefully'
    test)
  test_results: >-
    5/5 tests pass: parseSamples accepts a JSON array document, parseSamples rejects a non-array document,
    summarize aggregates outcomes and latency per node, summarize handles samples with missing metrics
    gracefully (NEW), renderReport prints one row per node with a header. Type check (tsc --noEmit) passes
    cleanly. Report command (npm run report) outputs correct nightly report with gw-04 showing n/a mean_ms and
    0 retries.
  bug_cause: >-
    In src/report.ts summarize(), the inner loop unconditionally accessed s.metrics.retries and
    s.metrics.latency_ms without checking if s.metrics exists. The data/samples.json fixture includes gw-04
    with outcome 'rejected' but no metrics field (the probe measurement cycle had not completed), causing a
    TypeError at runtime. The DeliverySample type also incorrectly declared metrics as required rather than
    optional.
  fix_summary: >-
    Two changes in the pipeline: (1) src/types.ts — changed metrics from required to optional (metrics?) and
    updated JSDoc to document the early-sample scenario. (2) src/report.ts — wrapped metrics access
    (totalRetries, latencySum, latencyCount) in if (s.metrics) guard so samples without metrics are counted
    for outcome tallies but excluded from latency/retry calculations (producing null mean_latency_ms and 0
    total_retries). The renderReport function already handled null mean_latency_ms via the 'n/a' fallback — no
    change needed there.
  residual_risk: >-
    Low. The fix is minimal (3 lines guarded + 1 character type change) and does not alter the behavior for
    fully-populated samples. All existing tests pass unmodified, and the new test covers both the
    partial-metrics node (gw-04 with 1 rejected + 1 delivered with metrics) and the fully-missing-metrics node
    (gw-05 with timeout only). The report command produces correct output against real data. No other call
    sites in the codebase need changes.
evidence:
  - source: 'terminal: cd /work/agent-codebench && npm run report (before fix)'
    summary: >-
      Crashed with TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading 'retries') at summarize() line 37 —
      confirms the bug is reproducible
  - source: 'terminal: cd /work/agent-codebench && npm test (after fix)'
    summary: 5/5 tests pass including new 'summarize handles samples with missing metrics gracefully' test
  - source: 'terminal: cd /work/agent-codebench && npm run report (after fix)'
    summary: >-
      Runs cleanly: gw-01 shows 2560.2 mean_ms, gw-04 shows n/a mean_ms and 0 retries — correct behavior for
      missing metrics
  - source: 'terminal: cd /work/agent-codebench && npm run typecheck (after fix)'
    summary: tsc --noEmit passes with zero errors — no type regressions introduced
  - source: src/report.ts:29-38
    summary: >-
      The fix: metrics access guarded by if (s.metrics) — retries and latency only accumulated when metrics
      are present
  - source: src/types.ts:9-17
    summary: >-
      metrics changed from required to optional (metrics?) with updated JSDoc documenting early-sample
      scenario
  - source: test/report.test.ts:49-86
    summary: >-
      New test: gw-04 has one rejected sample without metrics + one delivered with metrics; gw-05 has a
      timeout without metrics. Asserts correct outcome counts, total_retries=0 when no metrics,
      mean_latency_ms=null when no metrics, and correct partial mean for gw-04
risk_assessment: >-
  Low risk. The fix is surgical — a single guard block protecting three metric accumulations. The type change
  from metrics to metrics? is backward-compatible (existing callers that always provide metrics continue to
  work). No production deployments, credential rotation, or destructive actions were performed. The fix does
  not alter the output format or semantics for fully-populated samples.
next_action: >-
  Ready for PR: create a branch from main with these three file changes, submit with a Korean-language PR body
  describing the regression and fix, squash-merge after review.
durable_memory_decision: >-
  Nothing needs to be persisted to durable memory. This is a standard code-001 mission with no novel
  infrastructure, node configuration, or reusable process knowledge beyond the fix itself.
findings:
  - claim: summarize() crashes on samples without metrics field due to unconditional s.metrics access
    evidence:
      - >-
        terminal: npm run report before fix shows TypeError: Cannot read properties of undefined (reading
        'retries')
      - data/samples.json contains gw-04 sample without metrics
    confidence: high
  - claim: >-
      The DeliverySample type incorrectly declared metrics as required, masking the real-world scenario where
      probe cycles haven't completed
    evidence:
      - src/types.ts declared metrics without ?
      - >-
        JSDoc says 'Populated by the probe worker once the node's first measurement cycle completes' implying
        it may not always be present
    confidence: high
  - claim: The fix resolves the bug and all tests pass including the new edge-case test
    evidence:
      - 'terminal: npm test shows 5/5 pass'
      - 'terminal: npm run report produces correct output'
      - 'terminal: npm run typecheck passes'
    confidence: high
  - claim: Only three files were changed and the changes are minimal and targeted
    evidence:
      - 'src/types.ts: 1 character change (?), 1 JSDoc line added'
      - 'src/report.ts: 3 lines guarded inside if block'
      - 'test/report.test.ts: 1 new test function added'
    confidence: high
